==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*tauma-'' ‘pull, draw’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[tam|tām]] ‘bridle, progeny’, Old Saxon [[tom|tōm]], Old High German [[zoum]] (Dutch [[toom]] ‘rein, offspring’, German [[Zaum]] ‘bridle’), Old Norse [[taumr]] (Swedish [[töm]] ‘leash, rein’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /tæ:am/

===Noun===
'''tēam''' ''m'' (''pl'' '''tēamas''')
# [[childbirth]]
# [[family]], [[offspring]]
# a [[team]] of draught animals
# an Anglo-Saxon legal procedure in a stolen goods suit

